<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="357" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,463]" pageId="12" pageNumber="357">
Diagnosis. Wingspan 20.0–25.0 mm. Externally, 
<taxonomicName box="[782,984,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Eucosma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metamorphica">
<emphasis box="[782,802,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="357">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[822,984,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="357">metamorphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles the bicoloured form of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Dracontogena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kingstoni" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="357">D. kingstoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[261,321,296,319]" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(see below). The male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[699,781,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 46" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1745,1768]" captionTargetBox="[168,1435,469,1734]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,469,1757]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 46. Male genitalia in Dracontogena. 41. D. bernardi Karisch. (slide L. Aarvik 2808). 42. D. bernardi Karisch, phallus (slide L. Aarvik 2808). 43. D. solii n. sp. (slide NHMO 2010). 44. D. solii n. sp. phallus (slide NHMO 2010). 45. D. tonitrualis (Meyrick). 46. D. metamorphica (Meyrick). Scale figs. 41, 43: 1 mm., figs. 42, 44: 0.5 mm. Figs. 45 – 46 from Karisch (2005)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282275/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="357">
Fig. 
<number box="[751,781,295,319]" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" value="46.0">46</number>
</figureCitation>
) are distinct by the deeply excavate ventral edge of valva. The female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[406,536,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 60 – 63" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1924,1947]" captionTargetBox="[177,1407,216,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[161,1425,193,1903]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 60 – 63. Female genitalia of Dracontogena. 60. D. agassizi n. sp. (slide USNM 137,547). 61. D. agassizi n. sp. sterigma and sternite 7 (slide T. Karisch 1923). 62 – 63. D. metamorphica (Meyrick) (slide L. Aarvik 2011.025). Scale figs. 60, 62: 1 mm., figs. 61, 63: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282278/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="357">
Fig. 
<number box="[462,536,332,356]" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" value="62.63">62, 63</number>
</figureCitation>
) have sternite 
<number box="[710,724,333,356]" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" value="7.0">7</number>
deeply excavate with two membranous bands anterior of the excavation; segment 
<number box="[404,418,368,391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="357" value="7.0">7</number>
with conspicuous scale sockets anterolaterally; the sterigma large, becoming wider posteriorly; and the paired oval sclerites posterior of the sterigma small, separate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
